{% extends "layout-default.twig" %}

{% block content %}
    <div class="row">
        <ol class="breadcrumb">
            <li><a href="{{ links.home }}">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="{{ links.admin }}">Admin</a></li>

        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="row">
        {% if data_type =='content' %}
            <h3><small><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-file"></span></small> {{ definition.getName }}{% if definition.getTitle %} <small>({{ definition.getTitle }})</small>{% endif %}</h3>
        {% else %}
            <h3><small><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-wrench"></span></small> {{ definition.getName }}{% if definition.getTitle %} <small>({{ definition.getTitle }})</small>{% endif %}</h3>
        {% endif %}

    </div>
    <div class="row">

        <form class="well" role="form" method="post" name="form_admin" action="" id="form_admin">

            <fieldset>
                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-xs-7">

                        <textarea id="cmdl" name="cmdl" placeholder="" class="form-control formelement-tooltip"
                                  rows="35" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-placement="right"
                                  data-content="" data-original-title="" title="">{{ cmdl }}</textarea>


                    </div>
                    <div class="col-xs-1"></div>
                    <div class="col-xs-4">
                        <h4>CMDL Quick Start</h4>
                        <br/>

                        <div style="height:550px;overflow:auto">
                            <p>First write down, <strong>which</strong> <em>properties</em> you want to record, e.g. to
                                manage the news of your
                                company:</p>
<pre>
Name
Date
Location
Text
Abstract
Target Audience
Product
</pre>
                            <p>Now you already have a perfectly valid CMDL definition.</p>
                            <hr/>
                            <p>Next determine <strong>how</strong> you want to edit this <em>properties</em>:</p>

<pre>
Name
Date = date
Location = textfield
Text = richtext
Abstract = textarea
Target Audience = textfield
Product = textfield
</pre>
                            <hr/>
                            <p>As you can see the syntax is for each property is:
                            <pre>property = form element type</pre>
                            </p>

                            The form element type <em>textfield</em> is the default form element type, so you can leave
                            it
                            out.</p>
                            <hr/>
                            <p>Here's a list of most typical form element types:
                            <ul>
                                <li>textfield</li>
                                <li>email</li>
                                <li>link</li>
                                <li>textarea</li>
                                <li>richtext</li>
                                <li> html</li>
                                <li>checkbox</li>
                                <li>number</li>
                                <li>date</li>
                                <li>file</li>
                                <li>image</li>
                                <li>geolocation</li>
                            </ul>
                            </p>
                            <hr/>
                            <p>Most of the form element types can get specified in detail with additional
                                parameters.</p>

                            <p>Some form element type definitions do have mandatory parameters.</p>

                            <p>Let's have a look at <em>selection</em> and <em>reference</em> to complete our example:
                            </p>
<pre>
Name
Date = date
Location = selection (New York,Rio,Tokyo)
Text = richtext
Abstract = textarea
Target Audience = selection (B2B,B2C)
Product = reference product
</pre>
                            <p>
                                The form element type <em>selection</em> needs a list of options to select from, e.g.
                                "(New York, Rio, Tokyo)".
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                The form element type <em>reference</em> needs the name of the referenced content type
                                to display a select box with all records of that content type. In our example this would
                                be the content type "product".
                            </p>
                        </div>


                        <br/> <br/>

                        <p>
                            Take a look at the <a href="http://anycontent.readthedocs.org/en/latest/cmdl"
                                                  target="_blank">Content
                                Definition</a> section of the <a href="http://anycontent.readthedocs.org"
                                                                 target="_blank">AnyContent
                                documentation</a> for further information.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </fieldset>

            <hr/>

            <div class="controls">
                    <span class="btn-group">
                        <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary" id="form_admin_button_submit">Save</a>
                    </span>

                {% if data_type =='content' %}
                    <span class="btn-group">
                        <a href="{{ links.delete }}" class="btn btn-danger admin_button_delete_content_type">Delete</a>
                    </span>
                {% else %}
                    <span class="btn-group">
                        <a href="{{ links.delete }}" class="btn btn-danger admin_button_delete_config_type">Delete</a>
                    </span>
                {% endif %}
            </div>
        </form>
    </div>


{% endblock %}